tps%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa9f471fa-37c8-494f-b123-f4a2c02c3c65_900x785.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa9f471fa-37c8-494f-b123-f4a2c02c3c65_900x785.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa9f471fa-37c8-494f-b123-f4a2c02c3c65_900x785.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2 "><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div><figcaption class="image-caption"> Source: <a href="https://x.com/Mark_J_Perry/status/1747995005518516419">Mark Perry</a></figcaption></figure></div><p> This is generally a very good and important chart. It&#39;s not a <em>perfect</em> chart — it overstates college costs because it ignores financial aid, and its data source probably understates <a href="https://research.collegeboard.org/media/pdf/trends-college-pricing-presentation-2022.pdf">the recent drop in tuition</a> . Also, it puts housing in the red because housing went up in price in an absolute sense, even though wages went up by more. But these are minor quibbles — overall, the chart accurately conveys the fact that since the turn of the century, big-ticket services have gotten less affordable, even as many physical goods became more affordable.</p><p> But when you make “percentage increase” charts like this, the starting year you choose is very important. If you change the starting year, the trend often looks very different. And as Jeremy Horpedahl <a href="https://x.com/jmhorp/status/1750622296283189542">points out</a> , many of the big-ticket services that have gotten more unaffordable since 2000 have actually gotten more <em>affordable</em> since 2013: </p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F799ba5c6-f311-4746-87f8-95f86376db2b_900x654.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F799ba5c6-f311-4746-87f8-95f86376db2b_900x654.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F799ba5c6-f311-4746-87f8-95f86376db2b_900x654.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F799ba5c6-f311-4746-87f8-95f86376db2b_900x654.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F799ba5c6-f311-4746-87f8-95f86376db2b_900x654.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F799ba5c6-f311-4746-87f8-95f86376db2b_900x654.jpeg" width="696" height="505.76" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/799ba5c6-f311-4746-87f8-95f86376db2b_900x654.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:654,&quot;width&quot;:900,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:696,&quot;bytes&quot;:78904,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F799ba5c6-f311-4746-87f8-95f86376db2b_900x654.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F799ba5c6-f311-4746-87f8-95f86376db2b_900x654.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F799ba5c6-f311-4746-87f8-95f86376db2b_900x654.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F799ba5c6-f311-4746-87f8-95f86376db2b_900x654.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2 "><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div><figcaption class="image-caption"> Source: <a href="https://x.com/jmhorp/status/1750622296283189542">Jeremy Horpedahl</a></figcaption></figure></div><p> Hospital services are the big outlier here, but medical care in general has become a bit more affordable, as have college, day care, and housing.这真是个好消息。 It holds out some hope that the big service cost increases of earlier decades were a one-time phenomenon that&#39;s not going to be repeated.</p><p> Of course, that doesn&#39;t change the fact that we should look for ways to make health care, education, and housing more affordable. But it means that the headwinds stopping us from doing that may now have slackened. And it&#39;s an important reminder that economic trends aren&#39;t set in stone. </p><div><hr></div><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://www.noahpinion.blog/subscribe?&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Subscribe now&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"><a class="button primary" href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/subscribe?"><span>现在订阅</span></a></p><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/at-least-five-interesting-things-8ba?utm_source=substack&utm_medium=email&utm_content=share&action=share&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Share&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"> <a class="button primary" href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/at-least-five-interesting-things-8ba?utm_source=substack&utm_medium=email&utm_content=share&action=share"><span>分享</span></a></p>; 
Three holes in the U.S.' economic strategy against ChinaLegacy chips, drones, and coordination with allies. https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/three-holes-in-the-us-economic-strategy https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/three-holes-in-the-us-economic-strategyNoah Smith Tue, 11 Jun 2024 00:21:41 GMT <div class="captioned-image-container"><figure> <a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F475795ee-217c-4d8d-ac42-9976d60094c2_993x663.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F475795ee-217c-4d8d-ac42-9976d60094c2_993x663.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F475795ee-217c-4d8d-ac42-9976d60094c2_993x663.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F475795ee-217c-4d8d-ac42-9976d60094c2_993x663.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F475795ee-217c-4d8d-ac42-9976d60094c2_993x663.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F475795ee-217c-4d8d-ac42-9976d60094c2_993x663.jpeg" width="696" height="464.7009063444109" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/475795ee-217c-4d8d-ac42-9976d60094c2_993x663.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:663,&quot;width&quot;:993,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:696,&quot;bytes&quot;:68429,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:false,&quot;topImage&quot;:true,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F475795ee-217c-4d8d-ac42-9976d60094c2_993x663.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F475795ee-217c-4d8d-ac42-9976d60094c2_993x663.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F475795ee-217c-4d8d-ac42-9976d60094c2_993x663.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F475795ee-217c-4d8d-ac42-9976d60094c2_993x663.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" fetchpriority="high"></picture></div></a> <polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line><figcaption class="image-caption">照片由<a href="https://unsplash.com/@elimendeinagella?utm_content=creditCopyText&amp;utm_medium=referral&amp;utm_source=unsplash">Elimende Inagella</a>在<a href="https://unsplash.com/photos/grayscale-photo-of-round-metal-frame-zx7VUt9txos?utm_content=creditCopyText&amp;utm_medium=referral&amp;utm_source=unsplash">Unsplash</a>上拍摄</figcaption></figure></div><p>现在写这篇文章几乎感觉有点毫无意义。 The Biden administration isn&#39;t going to be able to do much more on the China front before election day, and if Trump wins, all bets are pretty much off in terms of China policy. But I think it&#39;s good to push these ideas into the general discussion anyway.</p><p> The transformation of US economic policy is <a href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/in-which-british-writers-scold-america">all about China</a> , and it&#39;s all about defense competition. As <a href="https://www.wsj.com/economy/the-u-s-finally-has-a-strategy-to-compete-with-china-will-it-work-ce4ea6cf">Greg Ip has written</a> , the new paradigm has three pieces — industrial policy, export controls, and tariffs. Tariffs protect militarily useful US industries from being devastated by sudden waves of Chinese exports, industrial policy builds up the US&#39; militarily useful industries, and export controls slow down China&#39;s development of military useful industries. There are some other benefits to these policies too — decarbonization, job creation, technological progress, etc. — but ultimately it&#39;s the defense balance between China and the developed democracies that&#39;s fundamentally driving everything here.</p><p> As general frameworks go, the Biden administration&#39;s three pillars aren&#39;t bad. Industrial policy has yet to be proven, tariffs can easily backfire and hurt US manufacturing if misused, and the export controls still contain lots of loopholes.但总的来说这是一个合理的方法。</p><p> It&#39;s not enough, though. It&#39;s pretty easy to identify at least three big remaining holes in the new policy approach.正如叶所说，“第四条腿，即与盟友建立统一的经济战线，仍然没有实现。” Tariffs, meanwhile, aren&#39;t easily able to target Chinese components if the final product is assembled outside China. And while industrial policy in the chip and battery industries is important, the US is still neglecting drones.</p><h4>阻止中国“传统”芯片为一切提供动力</h4><p>The US export controls on China are meant to prevent China from dominating the manufacturing of advanced cutting-edge semiconductors. There&#39;s little hope of <em>stopping</em> Chinese progress in chipmaking, but the hope is to slow down their progress to the point where the US and its allies can stay ahead. This is why the export controls and some other restrictions were designed with a “ <a href="https://georgetownsecuritystudiesreview.org/2023/12/26/u-s-economic-restrictions-on-china-small-yard-high-fence/">small yard, high fence</a> ” approach in mind.</p><p>但许多计算机芯片<em>并不</em>领先。它们是“传统”、“后缘”或“基础”芯片（三个术语含义相同）。 They are older tech that&#39;s much simpler to make — China already knows how to make them, and has the tools to make them in large numbers. Export controls have little or no hope of impeding China&#39;s progress in making legacy chips.</p><p> But just because legacy chips are technologically less sophisticated doesn&#39;t make them less important. As <a href="https://rhg.com/research/thin-ice-us-pathways-to-regulating-china-sourced-legacy-chips/">the Rhodium Group notes</a> , these chips power most of the things in our economy:</p><blockquote><p>传统芯片无处不在，因此至关重要。几乎所有电子设备（包括汽车、飞机和战斗机、医疗设备、智能手机、计算机以及农业和工业设备）均由成熟的节点芯片与领先的处理器相结合提供支持。与流行病相关的限制让人们认识到，缺少一个芯片可能会阻碍整个制造装配线，让消费者难以置信，他们的新车可能会被剥夺通常被认为理所当然的功能，比如自动加热和调节的座椅。</p></blockquote><p>目前，大部分芯片仍然在中国境外生产，但中国正在奋起直追，建造了大量新晶圆厂： </p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F16484902-0613-4b9a-804d-00a07fe3609f_1620x1635.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F16484902-0613-4b9a-804d-00a07fe3609f_1620x1635.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F16484902-0613-4b9a-804d-00a07fe3609f_1620x1635.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F16484902-0613-4b9a-804d-00a07fe3609f_1620x1635.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F16484902-0613-4b9a-804d-00a07fe3609f_1620x1635.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F16484902-0613-4b9a-804d-00a07fe3609f_1620x1635.jpeg" width="706" height="712.3035714285714" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/16484902-0613-4b9a-804d-00a07fe3609f_1620x1635.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:1469,&quot;width&quot;:1456,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:706,&quot;bytes&quot;:436430,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F16484902-0613-4b9a-804d-00a07fe3609f_1620x1635.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F16484902-0613-4b9a-804d-00a07fe3609f_1620x1635.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F16484902-0613-4b9a-804d-00a07fe3609f_1620x1635.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F16484902-0613-4b9a-804d-00a07fe3609f_1620x1635.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2 "><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div><figcaption class="image-caption">资料来源： <a href="https://rhg.com/research/thin-ice-us-pathways-to-regulating-china-sourced-legacy-chips/">荣鼎集团</a></figcaption></figure></div><p>这些新产能大部分将用于中国，为中国消费者生产产品。但其中大部分将直接出口，或嵌入汽车和电子产品等其他中国制造的产品中。 As we&#39;ve seen with autos and batteries, once China revs up its industrial machine and starts showering an industry with subsidies, it can be very hard for companies in other advanced countries to survive in the face of the onslaught. And legacy chips are one of China&#39;s <a href="https://csis-website-prod.s3.amazonaws.com/s3fs-public/publication/220523_DiPippo_Red_Ink.pdf?VersionId=LH8ILLKWz4o.bjrwNS7csuX_C04FyEre">most heavily subsidized</a> industries.</p><p> There are several ways this could hurt the US and its allies.</p><p> First, competition from China&#39;s legacy chip industry could swamp and destroy much of the chip industries of the US and its allies — Japan, Korea, Taiwan, and Europe, as well as the nascent chip industry in India.如果发生战争，这将使供应链面临危险。</p><p>它还将剥夺中国以外的芯片制造商用于资助尖端芯片开发的收入，使他们更加依赖政府补贴。 Destroying the legacy chip businesses of companies like TSMC, Intel, and Samsung could be China&#39;s answer to export controls.</p><p> And finally, there&#39;s the cybersecurity angle. Some people fear that Chinese-made legacy chips could come with built-in backdoors that would allow China&#39;s military to spy on Americans, disable US infrastructure, turn a bunch of US equipment and consumer products into bricks, or even take control of vehicles and crash他们。</p><p>因此，我们有很多理由试图阻止中国成为为其他国家制造传统芯片的国家。但如何做到这一点呢？ The Rhodium Group <a href="https://rhg.com/research/thin-ice-us-pathways-to-regulating-china-sourced-legacy-chips/">suggests various types of trade barriers</a> , including tariffs, to keep Chinese chips out of the US supply chain. And Chinese chips were included in Biden&#39;s <a href="https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefing-room/statements-releases/2024/05/14/fact-sheet-president-biden-takes-action-to-protect-american-workers-and-businesses-from-chinas-unfair-trade-practices/">recent round of tariffs</a> .</p><p> But you can&#39;t put a tariff on something you don&#39;t even see coming into the country. Currently, the US government has very little idea where the chips in its imports come from. If a car from Mexico or a laptop made in Thailand has a Chinese chip somewhere in it, the US government simply doesn&#39;t know about it. This means that although it&#39;s pretty easy to block imports of Chinese chips themselves, it&#39;s very <em>hard</em> to block imports of products that contain Chinese chips.</p><p> The first task, then, is to <strong>get good data</strong> on where all the chips in US imports come from. Right now, data on component imports only comes out from the OECD with <a href="https://www.nber.org/system/files/working_papers/w31820/w31820.pdf">a lag of several years</a> , and even that does not provide a product-by-product and company-by-company breakdown. The US needs to implement a reporting and inspection regime that gives the government good, up-to-the-minute information on where every computer chip in the country was physically made, which company owned the factory that made it, and which company designed it 。</p><p>数据显然是这里最重要的事情。但我们还可以采取一些其他政策措施，正如 Steven Glinert 最近在<a href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/americas-semiconductor-policy-is">Noahpinion 客座文章</a>中概述的那样。其中包括 A) 对用于设计传统芯片的软件的出口限制，以及 B) 对传统芯片制造商提供更多《CHIPS 法案》资金或类似补贴。这两者可能只会产生边际效应，但它们可以成为贸易壁垒的补充。</p><p>但实际上，数据才是关键。 You can&#39;t fight what you can&#39;t see, and currently, the US government can&#39;t see Chinese chips at all. I don&#39;t know of any current or planned government effort to identify Chinese chips in US imports.</p><h4>打造民用无人机产业</h4><p>US industrial policy, export controls, and tariffs are aimed at strategic industries — chips, autos, batteries, and so on. But there&#39;s a hugely important industry that seems to have left out of this effort so far: drones.</p><p>到目前为止，很多很多作家都<a href="https://www.technologyreview.com/2023/01/30/1067348/mass-market-military-drones-have-changed-the-way-wars-are-fought/">指出</a>无人机已经成为现代战争的必需品。在乌克兰，大量无人机被用于侦察、火炮瞄准、摧毁敌方车辆，甚至直接杀死敌方人员。如果您能忍受，我建议您观看一架小型玩具无人机，配备简单的爆炸装置，在乌克兰战场上<a href="https://x.com/JHartley2/status/1749495155915141203">追击并杀死一名俄罗斯士兵</a>。 That drone was piloted remotely by a human, but in the not-so-distant future, drones will be autonomous <a href="https://www.politico.eu/article/robots-coming-ukraine-testing-ground-ai-artificial-intelligence-powered-combat-war-russia/">AI-powered killing machines</a> . At that point, it&#39;s an open question of whether human soldiers will even be able to survive on the front lines of war.</p><p>基本上，有两种方式为无人机提供动力：内燃机和电动机。由内燃驱动的无人机往往更大、更重、更快、更强大。但电动无人机往往更便宜，并且可以大批量生产。 Shahed 无人机是最小、最便宜的内燃无人机之一，每架售价<a href="https://www.twz.com/news-features/what-does-a-shahed-136-really-cost">在 20,000 美元到 375,000 美元之间</a>。 In contrast, a DJI Mavic 3 costs <a href="https://www.google.com/search?q=mavic+3&amp;rlz=1C1RXQR_enUS1011US1011&amp;oq=mavic+3&amp;gs_&amp;sourceid=chrome&amp;ie=UTF-8">around $2,000</a> , while a larger Matrice 300 costs <a href="https://store.dji.com/product/matrice-300-rtk-and-dji-care-plus?vid=111261">around $13,000</a> . Both types of drones have their uses on the battlefield, meaning any country that can&#39;t build or easily procure cheap electric-powered drones in large numbers is now at a disadvantage in war.</p><p>目前，中国企业在商用电动无人机制造领域拥有<a href="https://dronedj.com/2023/12/12/top-drone-manufacturer-ranking-2023/">压倒性的高市场份额</a>，其中大疆创新占据主导地位。 The second-biggest company is the US&#39; Skydio, but they&#39;re still far behind DJI, and there are no other big US drone-makers.这意味着像乌克兰这样的现代战场正在被中国制造的产品所主宰。 And it means that if China ever goes to war with the US and its allies, the latter will find themselves without a lot of small electric-powered drones.</p><p> The US has <a href="https://theasymmetric.substack.com/p/missing-the-swarm-for-the-drones">considered banning</a> Chinese drones, but as far as I know, no one is talking about an industrial policy to build up the US&#39; <em>own</em> drone industry.拜登政府似乎将无人机视为类似于导弹或炮弹——一种弹药而不是一种车辆，因此只有军方需要购买。 But in a protracted war with China, a civilian US drone industry would provide important <em>surge capacity</em> for the US Military, much like automakers made tanks and airplanes during WW2.</p><p> One possible industrial policy to encourage the creation of a US commercial drone industry would be <em>deregulation</em> .美国联邦航空局已经大幅<a href="https://www.planeandpilotmag.com/article/faa-deregulates-small-commercial-drones/">放松了对小型商用无人机的监管</a>，但允许无人机在超视距 (BVLOS) 范围内操作将有很大帮助，因为这就是无人机在战争中的使用方式。 BVLOS deregulation is <a href="https://www.commercialuavnews.com/regulations/u-s-congress-set-to-mandate-faa-establish-uav-bvlos-final-rule">now in the works</a> in Congress, but it&#39;s not yet clear how meaningful the changes will be.</p><p> But although you can encourage drone consumption with deregulation, in the end you&#39;re limited by how many consumers actually want to buy drones.对于电动汽车和计算机芯片来说，这不是什么问题，但无人机是一个利基市场，即使在中国也是如此。通常，制造商需要一个庞大的消费市场才能扩大规模并降低成本。那么，中国企业是如何在无人机制造方面做到如此出色的呢？</p><p> Glenn Luk had <a href="https://www.readwriteinvest.com/p/why-is-china-so-good-at-making-drones">a great post about this</a> back in 2018, where he pointed out that most of the things that are used to make a <em>drone</em> are also used to make a <em>phone</em> .最大的例外是电动机本身，它更类似于搅拌机或其他家用电器中的电动机。</p><p> So a US industrial policy for drones would simply entail incentives for manufacturing drone <em>components</em> — electric motors, displays, cameras, etc. — in the US or select allied countries.这类似于《通货膨胀削减法案》激励国内电池制造的方式，而不是类似于《爱尔兰共和军》激励电动汽车本身制造的方式。对这些组件所使用的消费产品（电话、电器等）的最终需求已经存在（事实上，其中一些需求已经得到了爱尔兰共和军的补贴）。</p><p> This industrial policy wouldn&#39;t cost nearly as much as the IRA or the CHIPS Act, since electronics components other than chips and batteries are pretty cheap.但这可能有助于复兴国内消费电子行业，如果需要的话，该行业可以迅速转变为无人机行业。因此，尽管似乎没有人在谈论补贴电动机行业或显示器行业，但这似乎是一个有用的漏洞。</p><h4>统一战线</h4><p>It&#39;s important to remember <a href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/the-war-economy-sizing-up-the-new">how much bigger</a> China is than the US It has four times the population and twice the manufacturing capacity by value-added. Any protracted conflict between the two countries would see the US badly outmatched, despite its modest remaining advantages in some areas of technology. In other words, US national security relies crucially on <em>alliances</em> — in order to be able to stand up to a much bigger opponent, you need a gang.</p><p> While the US is pretty good at military alliances, it&#39;s not as good at <em>economic</em> alliances. To be fair, no one really is — economic relationships are much more multifaceted than defense cooperation, so there&#39;s no standard template for exactly how they&#39;re supposed to work. But there are a few areas where the US could cooperate more closely with allies in the quest to build a multinational economy capable of matching China&#39;s.</p><p> The most obvious area is <em>export controls</em> . The US needs countries like the Netherlands, Japan, Germany, South Korea, and Taiwan <a href="https://thediplomat.com/2024/05/the-missing-links-in-us-chip-policy/">to cooperate</a> if it&#39;s to have any chance of keeping cutting-edge chipmaking technology out of China&#39;s hands.到目前为止，拜登政府在这方面做得相当不错。</p><p> Second, the US should immediately pursue <strong>defense manufacturing collaboration</strong> among all its allies. The US&#39; withered defense-industrial base and lack of a commercial shipbuilding industry means will take time to fix;与此同时，美国应该严重依赖日本和韩国等伙伴来制造威慑中国所需的军事物资。 Fortunately, there are already <a href="https://asia.nikkei.com/Politics/International-relations/Indo-Pacific/Indo-Pacific-should-create-common-defense-market-Hudson-analyst-says">some moves in this direction</a> :</p><blockquote><p> The US and its allies in the Indo-Pacific are moving toward establishing a de facto &quot;common market&quot; for the defense industry, setting the same industrial standards and reinforcing each other&#39;s defense industrial base…The recent loosening of export controls among AUKUS partners…for经济学家兼国防分析师威廉·施奈德表示，建造核动力潜艇为盟国之间更多地区范围内的国防工业合作创造了机会……</p><p>施奈德表示，日本在工业层面开展此类防务合作的时机尤其成熟，因为该国拥有强大的造船能力。</p><p>五角大楼负责采办和保障事务的高级官员、副部长威廉·拉普兰特将开始与日本同行会面……讨论合作。 He will convene in Tokyo the inaugural meeting of the US-Japan Defense Industrial Cooperation, Acquisition, and Sustainment Forum, inviting representatives from American and Japanese defense contractors to discuss joint development, production and maintenance of weaponry…</p><p> “拉普兰特副部长正在推动的事情之一是联盟工业基地的概念，”施奈德说。</p></blockquote><p> A second area, which the US has done much less on, is <em>trade</em> .几个月前我写过这样的文章： </p><div class="digest-post-embed" data-attrs="{&quot;nodeId&quot;:&quot;abbd77ef-236c-47bb-b4ee-1170e2005286&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;The paradigm shift in U.S. economic policy began during the 2016 presidential election campaign. It was in that campaign that the candidates of both parties agreed on scrapping the Trans-Pacific Partnership (TPP). The TPP was a proposed free trade deal between the U.S. and a bunch of friendly Asian countries that &#8230;&quot;,&quot;size&quot;:&quot;sm&quot;,&quot;isEditorNode&quot;:true,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;The U.S. would be insane to go it alone on trade and manufacturing&quot;,&quot;publishedBylines&quot;:[{&quot;id&quot;:8243895,&quot;name&quot;:&quot;Noah Smith&quot;,&quot;bio&quot;:&quot;Econ blogger&quot;,&quot;photo_url&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/89fd964a-586f-461a-9f5a-ea4587d45728_397x441.png&quot;,&quot;is_guest&quot;:false,&quot;bestseller_tier&quot;:10000}],&quot;post_date&quot;:&quot;2024-04-05T01:06:01.900Z&quot;,&quot;cover_image&quot;:&quot;https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F73951205-b7b7-429e-b5c4-ad6533882105_1024x1024.jpeg&quot;,&quot;cover_image_alt&quot;:null,&quot;canonical_url&quot;:&quot;https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/the-us-would-be-insane-to-go-it-alone&quot;,&quot;section_name&quot;:null,&quot;id&quot;:143282101,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;newsletter&quot;,&quot;reaction_count&quot;:253,&quot;comment_count&quot;:102,&quot;publication_name&quot;:&quot;Noahpinion&quot;,&quot;publication_logo_url&quot;:&quot;https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fbucketeer-e05bbc84-baa3-437e-9518-adb32be77984.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F04281755-2cd6-42e5-a496-e69153abebb2_281x281.png&quot;,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true}"></div><p> China&#39;s strategic companies — Huawei, BYD, and the rest — have access to one gigantic market. By <a href="https://www.economist.com/finance-and-economics/2024/06/06/why-global-gdp-might-be-7trn-bigger-than-everyone-thought">some measures</a> , that market is even bigger than that of the US But the US, Europe, Japan, Korea, etc. would be an even <em>bigger</em> combined market.统一这些市场将使美国及其盟国公司——英特尔、波音、三星、丰田、空客、特斯拉、现代等——有能力扩大规模并降低成本。如果印度也加入进来，该集团将变得更大、更强大。</p><p> So to the degree that the US can forge its alliances into a <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/bidens-trade-challenge-kicking-the-china-dependency-habit-dfdb3a0">unified trading bloc</a> , it should.然而，挑战在于大多数其他国家并不愿意将中国从其供应链中剔除。如果该集团的其他成员只是充当中国商品的渠道，那么建立一个反华经济集团是毫无用处的。 The Biden administration has <a href="https://www.theguardian.com/business/article/2024/may/21/janet-yellen-eu-us-chinese-exports-tariffs-electric-vehicles">made some efforts</a> to get other countries to come along on Biden&#39;s tariffs, but these efforts will inevitably be very sparse and of dubious effectiveness.</p><p> One idea here would be to reward strategically important companies in allied countries with access to the US market in exchange for harmonizing their China trade policies with America&#39;s. Those companies would effectively be offered a choice — do business with the US or do business with China. Meanwhile, the US could ask allies to offer similar deals to its own companies in strategic industries.</p><p> Alternatively, if the US can manage to get good data on component sourcing throughout the supply chain, it could just enact free trade agreements with all its allies and then tax Chinese components.但这需要 A）更好地收集进口零部件的数据，以及 B）美国公众同意所谓的“贸易协议”。在两党共同努力推翻TPP之后，后者的前景显得黯淡。因此，这里真正的技巧是在不引发保护主义反弹的情况下获得贸易联盟的好处。</p><p>不过，总的来说，我认为更多关于经济联盟的言论，以及与盟友贸易和与敌人贸易之间的差异，将有助于美国公众为上述所有政策做好准备。 The US facing a rival bigger and more powerful than any we&#39;ve ever faced, and there&#39;s just no way we can go it alone. That&#39;s a message I don&#39;t expect Trump or his followers to be receptive to, which is why Democrats need to stand up and lead here. </p><div><hr></div><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://www.noahpinion.blog/subscribe?&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Subscribe now&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"><a class="button primary" href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/subscribe?"><span>现在订阅</span></a></p><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quo